T1  - Were price changes during the Great Depression anticipated?: Evidence from nominal interest rates
AU  - Evans, Martin
AU  - Wachtel, Paul
JO  - Journal of Monetary Economics
VL  - 32
IS  - 1
SP  - 3
EP  - 34
PY  - 1993
DA  - 1993/08/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(93)90033-C
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030439329390033C
KW  - Deflation
KW  - Monetary policy
KW  - Interest rates
KW  - Great depression
AB  - This paper reassesses whether the large swings in prices during the 1930's were anticipated. We argue that uncertainty about monetary, fiscal, and exchange rate policies induced systematic differences between the rate of price change expected by economic agents at the time and the time series forecasts of inflation. Our analysis of nominal interest rates and ex post inflation strongly supports this view. In fact. our results suggest that the deflation of the early Depression years and the inflation that followed were both largely unanticipated.
ER  - 

